    <title>Combined summary - block size - pay with difficulty</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T22:00:27.302457+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-September/010886.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The discussion begins with a debate on the feasibility of using difficulty or hashpower to change block size in Bitcoin. Jeff Garzik argues against such proposals, stating that they are unrealistic and potentially harmful to the block size and fee market, as they introduce unpredictability that makes planning difficult for businesses. Instead, he suggests researching neutral, forward-looking incentives like pay-to-future-miner.Gregory Maxwell disagrees with Jeff's position, arguing that most difficulty-based adjustments have small limits on the difficulty change and wouldn't cause significant changes in interblock times relative to orphaning. He also notes the successful use of pay-for-size schemes in some altcoins. However, there is concern about the unpredictability and volatility of the block size and fee environment, which makes planning difficult for businesses.The conversation also touches on proposals by BtcDrak and Greg Maxwell for increasing block size. BtcDrak proposes permanent increases through voting, while Greg Maxwell suggests temporary increases only for specific blocks. There are differences of opinion on the feasibility of difficulty-based adjustments, with rational game theory suggesting avoiding them even when the network desperately needs an upgrade, as they may lead to radical short-term changes in block size and fees.There is a trade-off between orphaning risk and centralization advantage, and mining is not a race. It was noted that Jeff's arguments against BtcDrak's proposal do not apply to Gregory Maxwell's original proposal where the block size is only increased for that specific block. An individual suggests using OP_CLTV for pay-to-future-miner instead of pay with difficulty, which is considered bad for everyone, including miners and users.Overall, the debate highlights the importance of predictability and stability in Bitcoin's markets and systems, and the need for further research into alternative approaches. The use of pay-with-difficulty is complex and difficult for all players to reason, making it a less viable option. There is a general problem with pay-to-increase-block-size schemes in that they indirectly set a minimal transaction fee, which could be difficult and arbitrary and goes against competition.</summary>
